  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="TK12">
<l>tuppārkkut tuppāya tuppākkit tuppārkkut</l>
<l>tuppāya tūu maḻai</l>            
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Rain—it fashions refreshing food for us to enjoy, and</l>
<l>while we enjoy, becomes refreshment.</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>
  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <head>Parimēlaḻakar</head>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK12_P1">
          (i-ḷ). uṇpārkku nalla vuṇavukaḷai yuḷavākki avaṟṟai yuṇkiṉṟārkkut tāṉumuṇavāya niṟpatūu maḻai, (e-ṟu).
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          The meaning ... : Rain—having brought into existence good aliments for those who eat and drink, it also becomes aliment itself for them while they are eating.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK12_P2">
          tāṉu muṇavātalāvatu taṇṇīrā yuṇṇappaṭutal. ciṟappuṭaiya vuyartiṇaimēl vaittuk kūṟiṉamaiyiṉ, aḵṟiṇaikku miḵtokkum. ivvā ṟuyirkaḷatu paciyaiyum nīrvēṭkaiyaiyum nīkkutaliṉ, avai vaḻaṅkivaruta luṭaiyavāyiṉa eṉpatām.
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          It also becomes aliment itself—that is, it is enjoyed as potable (lit. cool) water. Through expressing himself using (more lit. "placing at the top") the rational class [in "for those who eat" (uṇpārkku)], which has pride of place, [he implies that] this fits for the irrational class as well. In this way, [the verse] amounts to saying that [it is] through [rain's] removing living beings' hunger and desire for water [that] those [living beings] continue to exist.
        </p>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <head>Maṇakkuṭavar (19)</head>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK12_M1">
          (i - ḷ) piṟitoṉṟuṇpārkku avaruṇṭaṟkāṉa uṇavukaḷaiyu muṇṭākkit, taṉṉai yuṇpārkkut tāṉē uṇavāvatum maḻai, (e - ṟu).
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          The meaning ... : Rain—for those who enjoy another [food or drink], it brings [that] nourishment into existence for their enjoyment, and is itself also nourishment for those who drink it.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK12_M2">
          itu paciyaik keṭukku meṉṟatu.
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          This [verse says] that it destroys thirst.
        </p>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
